que amissione mala metiebatur ac desiniebat. Polyd. Virg. Ang. hist c. 23 p. 492. that at Christide having a shew of young women presented to him bare breasted, he immediately departed with these words;

In his fourth Book c. 10. he speaks of an interview between King Edward and Lewis the eleventh King of France;
Lib 2. c. 8. he shews that an interview between two great Princes for treaty of their affairs, hurteth more then profiteth. the French King after some discourse, said pleasantly, That he should come to Paris to solace himself there with the Ladies, and that he would give him the Cardinall of Bourbon for his Confessor, who would easily assoil him of sin, if any were committed. The King of England took great pleasure in this talk, and answered with a
merry countenance: for he knew the Cardinall to be a good fellow.
